The letter, after a translation distributed by Ströbele, has the following wording:
To the responsible
I was asked to write to you regarding your investigation into mass surveillance.
My name is Edward Joseph Snowden and I used to be contractual. on a direct employment as a technical expert at the National Security Agency (NSA), the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) and the United States Defense Intelligence Agency (DIA).
In the course of my employment in these institutions, I witnessed systematic violations of the law of my government, which caused me to act out of moral duty.
As a result of the publication of these concerns, I faced a serious and persistent incitement that forced me to leave my family and home.
I currently live in exile and enjoy temporary asylum granted to me by the Russian Federation in accordance with international law.
I am encouraged by the response to my political action, both in the US and elsewhere.
Citizens around the world, and also high officials - including the United States - have judged the revelations on a system of all-encompassing surveillance that is not accountable to anyone as a service to the public.
These espionage revelations drew many suggestions on new laws and guidelines aimed at the formerly covert abuse of public trust.
The benefits for society from these findings are becoming increasingly clear; at the same time, the risks accepted have been visibly reduced.
Although the result of my efforts has been demonstrably positive, my government continues to treat dissent as a breach of allegiance and seeks to criminalize and indict political expression.
But speaking the truth is not a crime.
I am confident that the United States government, with the support of the international community, will abandon this detrimental attitude.
I hope that, if the difficulties of this humanitarian situation are resolved, I will be able to participate appropriately and in accordance with the law in the responsible clarification of the facts concerning the statements made in the media, in particular with regard to the truth and authenticity of the reports.
I look forward to a conversation with you in your country once the situation is resolved and thank you for your efforts to uphold international law that protects us all.
Edward Snowden testifies by Hans-Christian Ströbele
