On the way through mud, rivers and jungle for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwelle brings free medical assistance to remote villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend treating hundreds of patients
There are not many doctors in the West African country, only one for 5,000 people
Vote here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is among the top 10 in CNN Heroes of 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other heroes in the top 10 to vote for the CNN Hero of the Year.
The winner will receive 250,000 dollars to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched as his sick father repeatedly lost consciousness and traveled to hospitals that did not have the means to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car crash near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon, in 1981.
At first he had only a broken arm, but then an inflammation formed, which spread to his brain and caused a hematoma there, which was to affect him for the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," according to Georges Bwelle.
We would have taken him out of Cameroon if we had had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father to overcrowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
"It's not easy," Bwelle comments.
You can leave the house at five in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, and yet you're not first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some people even die because they have to wait.
The situation has barely changed since Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor for 5,000 people each, according to the World Health Organization.
In contrast, the relationship in the United States is with a doctor for 413 people.
But even if there was a doctor for them, most Cameroonians could not afford the visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line and nearly three-quarters of the country's health spending is private.
"The only problem they have is poverty," says Bwelle.
And poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
His father and so many of his compatriots suffered to see the decision to do something about it in Bwelle.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team conducted 700 free operations last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and offers free medical care there.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped just under 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people squeeze into minibuses and drive with the laced medical equipment on the roof over unpaved terrain to the villages that need help.
Everything doesn't always go smoothly.
Already more than once they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they will receive like heroes: a feast, song and dance, and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a cause for celebration and a wave – with its broad smile and its limitless energy – is happy to be part of the cheerful celebration.
The next morning, the team then begins examining hundreds of patients.
"We treat 500 people per trip," says Bwelle.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometers around the village – and on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a number of areas.
Many people are treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses, or free birth certificates – a document required for school but simply cannot afford many poor families.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anesthesia.
The surgeries usually take place in a school, town hall or apartment; after the procedure, patients get up and go into the recreation area to make room for the next.
The lighting for the surgery and disinfection equipment is fed by the group's generator and so Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of Sunday morning.
It's an exhausting workload, but the village musicians usually help keep the team motivated.
"They drum all night so we can stay awake and continue our work," says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team then drives back to the city, tired but proud of the work done.
The group – a mix of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students – has performed 700 free surgeries last year and knows that with their work, it makes a huge difference to the people it helps.
One man explained that the free operation of a hernia, which he had received, now allows him to return to work.
"It's changing my family's future," said the man.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job, he finances 60% of his charitable activity, according to Bwelle; the rest comes from private donations.
"I really don't know when he's sleeping," says Katie O'Malley, who is studying medicine for the second year at Drexel University in Philadelphia and volunteers in Bwelle's group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so he can go on these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O'Malley, who come from the U.S. and Europe and support Bwelle, this is a chance to gain practical experience they would never get at home.
“We can be part of operations where we help to swab blood or the instruments for Dr. Keeping a wave," explains O'Malley.
That would never be possible in America as a second-year medical student.
Students usually pay for their trip to Cameroon themselves and frequently bring donated medical supplies.
But once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes over the accommodation, transport and instructions.
"He's undoubtedly a hero," says O'Malley.
He devotes his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no bounds.
For Bwelle, the almost constant work is not a burden.
Helping others to live a happier life and thus fulfilling a promise he has given his father gives him great pleasure.
"I'm so happy when I do this work," says Bwelle.
And I think about my father.
I hope he sees what I do.
I do it to make people laugh again and to ease the pain.
