Pope Francis appoints first cardinals in February
Pope Francis will be on 22. February first called new cardinals of the Catholic Church, the Vatican announced on Thursday.
Cardinals are the most senior clerics in the Catholic Church after the Pope and they are also the ones who elect a pope, so that Francis will appoint the first group of men who will ultimately participate in the election of his successor.
There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, a cardinal who has reached the age of 80 can no longer participate in the papal election – this is the case for a group of 120 “cardinals entitled to vote”.
In a statement in which the news was announced, Father Federico Lombardi, a spokesman for the Vatican, said that a meeting of all cardinals would take place before the ceremony to appoint the new cardinals, also known as a consistory, would be held.
"Pope Francis has decided to announce his decision to convene the consistory in February in advance so that other meetings that require the participation of cardinals from all over the world can be planned," Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said the number of eligible cardinals is likely to have dropped by February.
He explained that a pope usually appoints as many cardinals as necessary for the number of eligible cardinals to be 120 again, and as many cardinals over 80 as he would like.
Next year’s consistory is significant because it is the first since the election of Francis in March this year, according to Valero.
There is currently a certain overhang on the part of Europe and in particular Italy.
"It will be interesting to see if the new Pope will appoint cardinals from the rest of the world to restore balance," he said.
Forty percent of Catholics live in South America, but they have only a tiny number of cardinals.
The Cardinals will also be the first to be appointed since the formation of the Council of Cardinals established by Francis, a group of eight cardinals from around the world who are tasked with finding opportunities to reform the Church.
In the past, the Pope decided everything alone.
"Now Francis has chosen these eight cardinals to help him," Valero said.
He declared that it was "good that Francis was asking the cardinals for advice.
But so far we have not been in this situation – this is all completely new.
Valero said that typically the bishops would be called to cardinals from large places, but Francis was “full of surprises – so we don’t know who he’s appointing.”
