Scientists were able to shed more light on the connection between a dog’s tail wagging with its mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs with the tail wagged more to the right (from the dog's point of view) while it was the left side in nervous dogs.
But now scientists say that other dogs can perceive and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: "In humans, it is well known that the left and right hemispheres of the brain react differently to stimuli that evoke positive or negative emotions."
Here we tried to see this in other species.
He also noted that in dogs, just like in humans, the right hemisphere of the brain was responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in the feelings.
To learn more about how dogs react to the lateral tail swirling of their conspecifics, the researchers monitored the animals while these films of other dogs looked at each other.
They measured the heart rate of the four-legged friends and analyzed the behavior.
We will probably soon understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other
Professor Vallortigara said: “We showed the dogs movies with dogs – either a lifelike version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to use it to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right.”
When the animals saw an otherwise expressionless dog moving the tail to the right (seen from the perspective of the wagging dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail tendency was mainly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog who wags), so their heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, the dogs do not intentionally communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs would have learned from experience in which movements they should and should not worry about.
He said: "If you have different encounters with other dogs and the wagging with the tail in one direction is more associated with friendly behavior and the right side produces rather a less friendly behavior, then you react on the basis of these experiences."
The researchers say the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians and trainers gain a better understanding of their animal's emotions.
John Bradshaw, a dog behaviour expert and guest fellow at the University of Bristol's Faculty of Veterinary Medicine, explained this was not the first study to investigate whether left and right was important for dogs.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln found out that dogs turn their heads to the left when they look at an aggressive dog, and to the right when it comes to a satisfied dog.
In another research paper at the University of Victoria in Canada, the following said: “Dogs are more likely to approach a robot dog when his ‘tail’ wags on the left and not to the right, rather than to become restless – the other way around than in the Italian study.”
According to his statement, the differences could therefore stem from the fact that the dogs in the various studies did not interpret the animals in the films or the robot dogs as dogs.
A study of how dogs react to real dogs could help, he explained.
“Although there is considerable evidence for many different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many of the details still need to be determined – and dogs are no exception,” Bradshaw said.
However, since their behavior can simply be recorded, it will probably not be long before we understand why the tail sometimes moves in one direction, sometimes in the other.
