In fact, demand in parts of Southeast Asia – where household debt is increasing – is so great that ValueMax, where it made its swap, became the third pawnshop listed on the Singaporean stock exchange this week.
The pledges of jewelry are not only a quick way to get money – 1,300 Singapore dollars in the case of Janani Amirthalinga – but also almost as cheap as an unsecured bank loan.
Typically, pawnshops in Singapore demand an effective annual interest rate of 17 percent, just above the 15.4 percent that United Overseas Bank requires, a local lender with a branch in the same shopping center.
However, pawnshops offer the advantage that no review of creditworthiness or proof of income is required here, which is why loans are possible faster than with banks.
For this reason, millions of people in the region are turning to pawnshops after families feel the pressure from rising living costs as well as increasing household and consumer debt.
After five years of robust growth since the global financial crisis and cheap loans due to a loose fiscal policy in the developed economic areas, lower- and middle-income families are looking for pawnshops to make up for the difference in the stuttering economy.
This week, the rating agency Standard & Poor's described growing household debt, mainly due to rising mortgages, as a risk factor for Asian banks' creditworthiness.
Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt in Asia relative to gross domestic product, according to the agency.
