"In the end, this means that in the face of rising costs, people in the middle to lower segment (the income scale) will try to supplement their income wherever possible," says Song Seng Wun, an economist at CIMB, a Malaysian bank.
Historic highs in gold prices over the past two years have further reinforced the trend towards pledging personal items as people take the opportunity to turn the family's jewelry into cash.
In Singapore, about 70 percent of the pledged items are gold in the city-state's 200 pawnshops.
People say to themselves, "The price of gold looks good, let's pledge Grandmother's gold chain and get back next month."
The largest Thai pawnshop operator, EasyMoney, has experienced a 20 percent increase in customers in recent months in its stores.
The growth in the deposit business is so strong that ValueMax, operator of the branch in Bendemeer and 15 others in Singapore, wants to expand not only to neighboring Malaysia – where the company operates four houses – but also outside Asia, according to Yeah Lee Ching, Managing Director of ValueMax.
The company is financing that with 60 percent of Singapore's 66 million dollars, which it took this week with the IPO in Singapore.
While some lenders have fallen into the crossfire because of high interest rates, Yeah explains that pawnshops not only offer cheaper interest rates than other lenders, but also did not directly increase debt.
"Customers lend items they already own and the liquefying of personal valuables does not increase household training," she explains.
The pawnbroking business is increasingly accepted socially as short-term, hedged financing.
