Early puberty: Growing up faster
African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers, research shows.
Physical changes do not immediately mean puberty
There is no evidence that hormones or other chemicals are responsible
Experts believe epidemic obesity is a trigger of early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is less pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist who specializes in child health and family issues.
Should a mother be concerned if her daughter grows breasts and pubic hair at the age of seven or eight?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, the pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz that these early physical changes were relatively normal among American girls and represented a new norm.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring parents – usually this is not an indication that puberty is now occurring quickly,” Kaplowitz explained.
Obvious indications of the development, such as growing breasts, pubic and armpit hair as well as body odor, are evident in girls earlier.
Nevertheless, there has been only a slight shift in the age of the menarche (occurrence of the first menstrual bleeding) in the last 40 years.
In the United States, the average age is 12.5 years, slightly less than 12.75 in 1970.
"When the development of the breasts begins, it will take at least two to three years to go to the menarch," said Kaplowitz, also author of the book "Early puberty in girls: The essential guide to dealing with this common problem."
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty progresses.
It is controversial, which is actually the beginning of puberty, but it is "precocious" when breast augmentation is accompanied by a growth spurt before the age of eight.
In most cases, the process slows down or stagnant – something a pediatrician can closely monitor.
In the event of rapid progress, tests could be indicated by an endicronologist so that serious problems such as tumors or cysts can be ruled out.
There are treatment methods for delaying early menstruation and defending against another consequence: the premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to growth inhibition and thus small body growth in adults.
The recommendations for drug or hormonal therapy are based on the age of the child, the developmental speed, the growth rate and the emotional maturity.
Psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is reluctant to use medication, but he admits: “Suppressing puberty can mitigate behavioral problems and girls’ feelings of being unlike their peers.”
The other big problem is understandable: parents just don't want their very young daughters to have the period.
"They worry about the risk of pregnancy or how they handle the hygienic side," Kaplowitz said.
"It was a shock," recalls a woman whose daughter got her days at the age of ten.
Even if there were first signs and we had talked about menstruation, she was not emotionally prepared.
She came home terrified and excited from school because she was the first in her circle of friends.
There are many comprehensively published theories about the causes of early puberty.
But there is no conclusive evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment or sexual messages in the media are the cause.
Boys, like girls used to, come into puberty.
Kaplowitz believes that the most convincing premise is the epidemic of obesity.
He supported conducting a study in 2001 on girls aged six to nine, which establishes a link between body fat and entry into puberty.
Other research supports this conclusion, but there are many other factors that played a role.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty rather than their white peers.
There are different explanations for this.
Globally, early puberty seems to be influenced by all sorts of things, from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another mystery: Although boys have grown the facial and pubic hair earlier, the trend towards full previous puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other doctors at the AAP conference underlined the complexity of the issue.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair is common even in babies and toddlers.
"We need to be careful how we identify the true beginning of puberty," Dr. said. Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children's Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to seek advice from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
"This can mean having to have a conversation sooner than expected," Kaplowitz advised.
If you stay calm, the child usually reacts well.
Girls who blossom early need the insurance that the process is a normal part of life, even if it occurs earlier than thought.
