Royal Commission hearing: Two YMCA staff accused of sexual offences against Jonathan Lord charges
Two YMCA employees from New South Wales (NSW) were charged with sexual offences in connection with children before allegations were made against the child care worker Jonathan Lord from Caringbah in 2011, as the Royal Commission for Child Sexual Abuse learned.
But at the opening statement to the commission, the YMCA had stated that it had "never had to deal with an incident of child sexual abuse in the organization."
Managing director Phillip Hare was questioned about a case in which a YMCA employee had been charged with misdemeanours with child pornography, and another in which one sports teacher from YMCA Caringbah Hall had been convicted of abusing children entrusted to him in 1991.
Hare told Gail Furness, a commission-assisting lawyer, that he knew about the first case but did not know the second.
He acknowledged that the opening statement of the YMCA to the Commission was also inaccurate in the claim that "there have been external reviews of the YMCA in which the YMCA has been recognised as at the forefront of child safety."
Rather, evidence before the Commission shows that the YMCA has been informed that it has received the second lowest rating of four possible in a Department of Education and Communities quality audit in August of that year.
Hare, who started at the YMCA at 21, acknowledged that the management had failed "from me down" in hiring Lord and did not ensure that staff had been aware of their obligations to report violations of the child safety guidelines.
Lord had been convicted earlier this year of sex offences against twelve boys during his two-year work for the YMCA.
He was sentenced to at least six years in prison.
Hare denied, however, that the YMCA had a cultural problem that had prevented staff from reporting Lord's violations regarding the safety of children.
Staff testified they had witnessed violations, including that Lord was alone with children, caring for them privately as babysitters, letting them sit on his lap, said to one that he loved it, and had children play with his mobile phone.
Danielle Ockwell, whose supervisor was Lord and who had asked for a child protection training because she was concerned about his behavior, testified that the child service manager Jacqui Barnat, who was Lord’s superior at the YMCA Caringbah, was “very intimidating and very aloof most of the time.”
The managing director explained that he would not accept statements from employees that they did not dare to report to their superiors.
Instead, he said, their friendship with Lord had affected their judgment, which is why they had not reported him.
Hare said he had told the YMCA NSW board that the lesson the organization had to draw from the "Jonathan Lord incident" did not involve reporting by employees, and the board had agreed to him.
Hare said the decision to urge employees to sign secrecy obligations shortly after the allegations emerged had been taken by the YMCA's chief executive of the YMCA's children's services, Liam Whitley.
He said that this was to prevent contamination of the evidence, but this had been "overzealous" and poorly implemented.
The YMCA NSW was not a child-safe organization during the time when Jonathan Lord was employed there between 2009 and 2011, explained Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University, a child sexual abuse expert, the commission.
He explained that there had been "serious problems" in hiring, reviewing, training, training and supervision of employees.
The hearing was until 20. December adjourned.
Tourism: Descent to the Romans
At a length of around 120 metres, a sewer from the Roman period is preserved below Cologne.
If you visit Cologne, you can’t miss the cathedral.
The two towers rise up to the sky for around 157 metres and make it the second tallest church building in Europe.
But only a few visitors, who marvel at the two delicate church towers, suspect that there is also a lot to discover under the cathedral.
Rainer Schulze is an expert in Cologne’s underworld.
The meeting point for its guided tours is the service center of Cologne tourism directly at the cathedral.
The tour begins quite unspectacularly: "We start in the underground car park," says Schulze.
In the seventies, the city fathers wanted a car-friendly city, and therefore of the remains of the old city wall only what was not too big stopped.
Most users of the car park therefore rush past the Roman remains today and only park their car.
But if you take a closer look, you will discover an archaeological site separated by metal grid rods in the parking deck D2.
On display are about five-metre-high ruins made of palm-sized stones.
"It's remnants of the Roman city wall that was built in the second half of the first century AD," Schulze recounts.
Before it goes back to daylight, Schulze lets the participants on the upper park level take a look in a dark, 15-meter-deep shaft.
This is the fountain of the old cathedral, which is unfortunately hardly noticed.
Next stop of the tour is the Praetorium, and here the participants descend again into the depths.
We experience here the official seat of the once most powerful man north of the Alps, the Praetor of the CCAA.
What CCAA means, a visitor wants to know.
"The abbreviation stands for "Colonia Claudia Ara Agrippinensium", which in good German means "City of Roman Law and City of the Agrippinensians, founded under Emperor Claudius at the site of the altar for the imperial cult"".
And the praetorium is the former governor's palace, the power center of the Roman Empire on the Rhine.
From the anteroom of the exhibition, a tunnel access leads to the Roman sewer, which is preserved here at a length of around 120 metres.
"You can walk along a piece along the so-called Cloaca Maxima if you want," Schulze cheers up the guests.
Schulze still has a surprise.
After getting the key at the cash register, he leads the group to a 16-meter-deep, walk-in shaft.
"We're in the mikveh now, a ritual Jewish bath," he explains.
The Jewish community built their bath deep into the ground to get to the groundwater that was indispensable for the ritual washes.
To this day, in the lower end of the mikvah, whose origins date back to the eighth century, different water levels can be read through changing levels of the Rhine.
The mikveh will become part of an archaeological zone on the town hall square, for which construction work is to begin shortly.
However, a few years will pass before completion.
