George Kerevan: European unbundling gives the Scots a choice
A new day, a new story of terror to independence.
This time we are warned that an independent Scotland is needed to join the Schengen area as a condition for EU membership.
That provides the keyword for stories about passport checks in Berwick and a barbed-wire-secured border along Hadrian's Wall.
In fact, the Strathclyde bill highlighted the potential economic benefits that would bring more freedom of travel in the rest of Europe, but this did not matter in the headlines, as expected.
No one has mentioned that the EU member states often bend their strict rules if it is cheaper for them.
Since Scotland is not currently part of the Schengen area, continued non-compliance with Brussels would only be a small concession in return for what you really want from the Scots.
So actually no story.
And one that has already come in the year that it is already like a fossil: For the first time I have heard the "independence means passport control" duck at least 40 years ago.
An interesting point is lost in the constant repetition of this ancient history.
Why should one expect an independent Scotland to dance to the European pipe?
Why trade the London yoke for that of Brussels, especially now?
This is the real European news: the great plan for the unification of Europe, which was drawn up after the war, has stalled.
With the euro crisis, the Europe project has officially died.
Everywhere in the EU, parties that are anti-EU or want to throw the euro overboard as a single currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party – founded only this year – was able to secure almost five million votes in the federal election in September and thus effectively expel the Free Democrats (the equivalent of the British Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag.
There has always been domestic opposition to the plan to create a federalist Europe.
The current economic crisis, however, turns out to be a turning point.
Because of the strict austerity policy imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank in connection with the straitjacket, into which the respective national economy is forced by sticking to the common currency, many people are of the opinion that the Europe project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with the fact that national governments are causing excessive budget deficits – that was only the case in Greece.
Instead, the Eurosystem has nailed its members to exchange rates that are beneficial for German exporters – and German politicians would like to leave that.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the local currency, southern Europe finds itself with a built-in productivity disadvantage over Germany.
The only way is to cut wages and public spending – spurred by Berlin.
Behind the current budget and currency problems lies a deeper European productivity problem.
As a result of the "green" energy directives prescribed by Brussels - a code for subsidising French and German energy companies at the expense of consumers - European industry pays double for electricity and four times for gas compared with the United States.
That's a crippling cost disadvantage, as we could already see in Grangemouth.
All of the world's wage fixed-ins are not protecting the European petrochemical industry from being cornered by cheap American shale gas.
As a result, a revolt is coming up, especially in France, the former cheerleader of the EU.
After the war, France's political elite saw the EU as a vehicle with which to keep Germany at bay and lift Paris on equal footing with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a gateway to political legitimacy and has imposed its own economic policy on Europe, with which the ailing French economy is struggling.
The result: Marine Le Pen's right-wing, anti-EU Front National has just won a decisive by-election, pointing the ruling Socialists to third place.
The Front National is now the most popular party in France with 24 per cent of the electoral vote – a timely warning for the British Labour party that it cannot assume a split in the right-wing spectrum would automatically mean benefits for the left.
What does Le Pen do with their newfound popularity among the white French of the working class?
She wants to use the EU elections next year to forge an anti-EU, anti-Community currency bloc in the European Parliament.
If the anti-EU parties do well in these elections – and this is very possible – then for the first time such a bloc could dominate the European Parliament.
This is the point to which I want to go: in the not too distant future, the growing resentment against the EU and the common currency will come together to abolish the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will become something like the "Europe of (sovereign) nations" that General de Gaulle favored.
Germany and a few of its satellite economies may be sticking to the euro, but France and southern Europe will return to their own currencies.
I expect Britain to distance itself from this project in the hope of ingratiating itself with the US.
However, Washington's growing interest in the Pacific suggests that Britain alone will stand in the Atlantic rain.
Where is Scotland with all this?
We can decide to be a region of (in the last consequence) of Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests – including saying Berlin and Brussels what they can put where.
I suspect Scotland could drive quite well in a looser European network, provided we keep our own currency.
Cooperation with other similar countries is easier in an unfederated Europe of nations.
Otherwise, we should consider doing the same to Norway and retain our economic independence.
The SNP government in Scotland is – remarkably – the most successful political movement against austerity in Europe and won a spectacular majority in 2011 due to the rejection of the proposed (and made) cuts that Labour Finance Minister Alistair Darling and the subsequent Tory-Lib Dem coalition had to answer for.
It would be ridiculous for Scotland to opt for independence now, only to then be forced to impose an austerity policy on Berlin and Brussels.
FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices on aircraft (but not make mobile phone calls)
Air travelers can now use their electronic devices to read, work, play, listen to music and watch movies from departure to landing, but not make phone calls, according to the new guidelines issued Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the U.S.
But passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
How quickly they would be implemented depended on the respective airline, FAA employee Michael Huerta explained at a press conference.
Airlines must demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new guidelines and that they have updated the training manuals of the air service personnel as well as the regulations for the storage of the devices in accordance with the new regulations.
The FAA said it had already received plans from some airlines that would like to expand the use of portable electronic devices on aircraft.
Among those airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the condition of the plan, we could approve the expanded use of electronic devices very soon," the FAA announced in a statement.
Currently, passengers will have to turn off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They are not allowed to take them off again until the plane has reached an altitude of three kilometres and the captain gives the green light.
When entering the landing approach, passengers must switch them off again and must not take off again before the plane has landed.
According to the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are secured against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices even on take-off, landing and on the tarmac, the FAA said.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft converted for the use of Wi-Fi at larger heights should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the professional association of professional flight attendants, welcomed the changes.
“If the new regulation is safely implemented – and we work closely with the airline in this regard – both sides will benefit from this,” Glading commented.
We're honestly tired of having to feel like guards on this issue.
Nevertheless, Internet connections for surfing, exchanging e-mails, text messages or downloading data below three kilometers remained prohibited, the authority explained.
Passengers are encouraged to put smartphones, tablets and other devices into flight mode.
So still no "Words With Friends," the Scrabble-like online game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011, when he had to publicly leave an American Airlines jet because he refused to shut down the device while the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices such as laptops must continue to be stowed away, as there is a risk of injury here if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile phone calls during the flight will also remain prohibited.
Regulatory competence for telephone conversations lies with the Federal Communications Commission (FCC), not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices on take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the Road Safety Administration National Transportation Safety Board, safety expert on national transportation issues on CBS News, said cell phones were still considered a risk.
“Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they could potentially cause interference with navigation devices, but because we from the FCC know that transmission from the air can also disrupt transmission masts,” Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee launched by the FAA to investigate this issue last month recommended that the government allow a wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, pressure has increased on the FAA to ease restrictions on use.
Critics such as Missouri Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill argue that there are no valid security reasons for the ban.
The restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
In some studies, there is talk that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore the shutdown of the device.
The FAA began to restrict the use of electronic devices by air travelers in 1966, after reports of disruptions to navigation and communication devices by passenger-carried FM radios became known, which at the time represented the latest technology trend.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA that they do not care about electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering Wi-Fi to passengers for several years when altitude is reached.
The aircraft adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also less sensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for greater use of electronic devices under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today's electronic devices generally provide much less radio radiation than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, only emit minimal radiation when turning over.
But when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
Among the advocates of easing restrictions on device use by passengers is Amazon.com.
In 2011, company employees loaded a passenger plane full of Kindle e-readers and made a test flight to determine problems, but could not detect any.
Members of the FAA advisory committee expressed mixed feelings about the risk of using equipment.
Douglas Kidd of the National Association of Airline Passengers said he felt the disruption caused by the devices was real, even if the risk was minimal.
Other committee members said there were only isolated reports of pilots talking about a disruption of aircraft systems by the devices, and most of them were very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to arrange the shutdown of the devices by passengers in the event of an instrument landing in poor visibility conditions.
A grouping from the travel industry welcomed the changes, calling them a reasonable adjustment for travelers who would be extensively equipped with technology today.
"We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that a pleasant passenger experience is not at odds with safety," said Roger Dow, CEO of U.S. Travel Association.
