"We want to involve the inhabitants in the planning at an early stage," opened Mayor Jens Häußler the citizen information event on the flood protection concept in Gechingen.
Around 80 participants had come to the municipal hall to be explained the planned measures, to ask questions, to express concerns and to contribute ideas.
Häußler clarified: "The final decisions are made by the members of the local council".
The flood, the Gechingen on the 15. May 2009, hit unprepared, was a drastic event that raised the question of protective measures for the future, according to Häußler.
A river basin survey had been commissioned with the neighboring municipality of Aidlingen, which is now the basis for the flood protection concept in Gechingen.
"The protection of as many built-up plots as possible is the goal," says Häußler.
The planning is based on the protection against a flood that is statistically expected every 100 years according to the German Weather Service.
Climate change is taken into account by a 15 percent surcharge.
In expert circles, this is referred to as "HQ 100aKlima".
The water masses, which had caused considerable damage in Gechingen in 2009, corresponded to a 1000-year flood.
"There is no absolute protection, but we can achieve a relative improvement," says Häußler.
In order to achieve the protection HQ 100aKlima, around four million euros must be invested in Gechingen, with the municipality being able to expect state grants of around 70 percent.
Häußler pointed out, however, that the funding would only exist if an overall concept was implemented.
For this purpose, the municipality is dependent on the participation of the citizens.
An elaborate planning and approval procedure must be completed.
