New anti-nicotine vaccine could eliminate the pleasure of smoking
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could spoil the fun of smoking.
A single dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice from nicotine addiction for a lifetime.
More experiments are needed before human testing, which can take a few more years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said the initial results were good.
“We are very hopeful that this type of vaccination strategy can once help millions of smokers who have tried to quit and have tried all the methods available on the market, but have had to experience that their nicotine addiction is stronger than these approaches,” Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been altered to contain the genetic information for the production of nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then produce a constant stream of antibodies.
The antibodies hunt the nicotine molecules in the blood and neutralize them before they reach the brain, so that a smoker does not experience a nicotine high.
In trials, vaccinated mice given nicotine retained their normal level of activity.
Mice without vaccination, on the other hand, would have taken a "time out," the researchers explained, a sign that the nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
The vaccinations had to be given so frequently to maintain the antibody level that they were expensive and impractical.
Yet the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be significantly lower, because it is turning liver cells into antibody factories.
As Professor Crystal said, a future vaccine for people, if it is quite sure, could be given to children before they were tempted to try a cigarette, thus preventing nicotine addiction.
More likely, however, is that smokers would use it to stop.
“They know that when they start smoking again, they no longer feel any pleasure because of the nicotine vaccine, and that helps them to put off the habit,” he explains.
