The usually rather boring area of road planning has suddenly sparked intense debate with colorful alliances.
Libertarians have allied themselves with environmental groups and are in favour of the government using the small boxes to record the kilometres driven – and possibly where they were driven – and then use the information to calculate tax assessments.
The Tea Party is horrified.
The American Civil Rights Association (ACLU) is also deeply concerned and expresses a number of privacy concerns.
But while Congress cannot agree on a course of action, several states are no longer waiting.
They are currently examining how they can switch over the next ten years to a system where drivers pay per mile driven.
Thousands of motorists have already tested the tachographs, some of which are equipped with GPS surveillance.
This is really a must for our country.
"It's nothing we're just potentially going to use," said Hasan Ikhrata, executive director of Southern California Assn. of Governments, which is planning a record of miles driven by all California motorists in the state from 2025.
The way we pay those taxes will change.
The technology for that is there.
The initiative comes at a time when the Highway Trust Fund, which is funded from the taxes that Americans pay at the pump, is broke.
But in America, there is not as much fuel as before.
Cars use less gasoline.
The state petroleum tax of 18.4 cents per gallon (less than 4 euro cents per litre) has not risen in 20 years.
Politicians, at high fuel prices, do not dare to raise the tax even by a penny.
"The gasoline tax is simply not future-proof," said Lee Munnich, an expert in traffic legislation at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently equipped 500 cars with tachographs to test a mile-based payment system.
"This represents the most sensible alternative in the long term," he said.
Bureaucrats refer to it as a mile-based user fee.
It is not surprising that the idea is appealing to urban liberals, because the tax could be used, for example, to influence the driving behavior in such a way that traffic jams and climate-damaging exhaust gases are reduced.
California planners are relying on the system in developing strategies to achieve the state’s ambitious, legally enshrined climate change goals.
But Republican Bill Shuster of Pennsylvania, chairman of the House Transportation Committee, has also stated that he sees it as the most viable long-term alternative.
The free marketers of the Reason Foundation are also impressed by the idea of having drivers paid after the distance travelled.
"This is not a tax that disappears into a black hole," explains Adrian Moore, vice president of guidelines at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The movement is also backed by two previous American transportation ministers who, in a report in 2011, had urged Congress to move toward miles-based billing.
The U.S. Senate last year approved a 90-million-dollar pilot project that would have included 10,000 cars.
Yet the majority in the House of Representatives prevented the push, responding to the concerns of MPs from rural areas representing people who often have to travel many miles in everyday life on their way to work or to the city.
Nevertheless, several states and major cities are moving in this direction on their own.
Most engaged is Oregon, which currently recruits 5,000 drivers for the country's largest experiment.
These drivers will soon pay the mileage fees to the state instead of the petroleum tax.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York City is also considering one.
Illinois is testing it to a limited extent with trucks.
And the I-95 coalition, which includes the transportation ministries of 17 states on the East Coast (including Maryland, Pennsylvania, Virginia and Florida), is currently investigating how to introduce the change.
The concept is not a universal hit.
In Nevada, where recently 50 volunteers were equipped with the equipment, motorists were skeptical at the thought that the government could track each of their movements.
"Concerns about Big Brother and such things were a big problem," explains Alauddin Khan, head of strategy and results management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
People didn't want to.
When the test started, Nevada's ACLU warned on its website, "It would be relatively easy to turn the tachographs into adult monitoring devices."
There is no need to build a gigantic, bulky technological infrastructure that would inevitably be used to capture data on the daily movements of individuals.
Nevada is among a number of states that are now looking for affordable technology that the state can use to capture the kilometers they have driven, but not exactly when and where.
With that, Khan says, the public would also be more reassured.
The hunt for this technology has led some authorities to a small startup company called True Mileage in California.
The firm originally did not compete to help states with the taxation of motorists.
Rather, their goal was to gain a foothold in an emerging market for car insurance, where drivers are supposed to pay based on the miles driven.
But the devices it tested are also interesting for the street planners, because they do not work with GPS and provide only limited information, which is regularly uploaded by modem.
"People are more willing to participate if their speed and locations are not recorded," said Ryan Morrison, managing director of True Mileage.
In some of these public pilot programs, big mistakes have been made.
There are significantly cheaper and less intrusive ways to implement this.
In Oregon, planners are experimenting with giving motorists a range of choices.
You can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they don't choose any equipment at all and instead pay a flat fee based on the miles driven by all state residents on average.
Other bodies hope to sell the concept of a suspicious public by equipping the devices with more features than with fewer.
In New York City, traffic officers want to develop a taxable device that also pays for parking fees, only has to pay insurance for kilometers driven, and speed data is collected in real time by other vehicles, thanks to which motorists can avoid traffic jams.
"Motorists would be motivated to participate by the added value of the benefits offered by the system," a city planning document reads.
Some transport planners, however, wonder whether all the talk about paying per mile is not just a huge distraction.
At the Metropolitan Transportation Commission for the San Francisco Bay area, officials said Congress could solve the bankrupt Highway Trust Fund's problem simply by raising the fuel tax.
An additional one-off fee or annual levy could be imposed on motorists with hybrid vehicles or other vehicles that consume little petrol, so that they also pay a fair share.
"There is no reason for an operation if an aspirin is enough," explains Randy Rentschler, the Commission's head of legislation and public affairs.
When we do that, hundreds of millions of motorists worry about their privacy and numerous other things.
