The Times has a copy of the upcoming book, and it reported Thursday night that the president's top advisers had conducted "extensive group meetings and polls in late 2011" to find out if it looked better for Obama's dwindling hopes of re-election if he dropped Biden.
According to Jonathan Martin, national policy correspondent for the Times, the book thoroughly traces the history of the efforts of leading campaign and White House employees, namely the former White House Chief of Staff Bill Daley, to measure the effect it has on the poll ratings to swap former Secretary Clinton for the vice president.
The potential change was a tightly-guarded secret within the Chicago and Oval Office campaign infrastructure.
Only half a dozen of the president's closest advisers - including Daley, Obama's former campaign director, Jim Messina, and the former White House senior adviser, David Axelrod and David Plouffe - knew about the proposed change.
In Double Down, it is claimed that Daley was at the forefront of the effort to exchange Biden despite her "close, personal relationship" before finally deciding against such a move, after the data showed that Clinton's candidacy would "not significantly improve Obama's chances."
In an interview with Martin, Daley confirmed that the administration had actually considered replacing Biden with Clinton.
"I expressed a whole range of things to consider, and that was one of them," Daley told the magazine.
It must be remembered that the president had terrible poll ratings at the time, so we thought, "For God's sake, what do we do?"
While Daley called the investigations "bid care," Martin told CNN's Anderson Cooper that significant effort had been put into the campaign for re-election to find out if such a move would pay off in terms of the ballot boxes.
"In campaigns, not as much money is spent on surveys and focus groups if you don't seriously think about something," Martin explained on AC360.
It is not clear, however, whether Obama knew his team was thinking about an exchange.
Martin told CNN he asked Daley if his then-boss had known about the potential change.
Although Daley said he did not believe the president was “conscious” of the possible change, the former chief of staff admitted that it was “possible” for Obama to know about it.
Martin added that “double down” did not provide a definitive answer to the question of whether the political probing had reached Obama’s desk.
