Desperation cry of an Obama voter
I have elected President Obama twice in hopes that change is possible
He says Obama has made laudable efforts that have been thwarted by Republicans' blockade tactics
The blockade policy doesn't excuse Obamacare's website issues, the drone strikes
Obama's memoir about the 2008 election campaign is a sad reminder of what would have been possible
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year student at Harvard Medical School.
I am currently reading a terribly sad book.
It's a book I believed would sneer up during the gloomy second year of my medical studies and give me hope again.
It's called "The Audacity to Win" and describes the memoirs of Barack Obama for the 2008 presidential election.
When I’m done with my patient transcripts in the evening and go to bed, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and could take a speech away.
The election became a landslide victory and news anchors paused to show the historical significance of this hour.
My classmates cried with joy and my parents gathered all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was on their way to the White House and the nation was ready for change.
When Obama moved to office in 2008, he had approval ratings of 82%.
And then I close the book.
Switching to the present again is a rude awakening, as if being torn from a dream.
It’s hard to remember these optimistic times – they seem to be a vague reminder, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I first cast my vote, something has actually changed.
But it's just nothing I could have imagined.
I recognize the great and versatile things Obama has achieved, from the passage of the Affordable Care Act for health insurance to the military withdrawal from Iraq, the end of forced secrecy of homosexuality in the Army, and the killing of Osama bin Laden.
I, too, believe that partisan blockade tactics have tipped too many aspirations that our nation should be brought forward with: immigration reform, a public option for health insurance and the closing of Guantanamo Bay, to name a few.
But after defending the Obama administration to colleagues and acquaintances countless times, I ended up with my attempts at explanation.
I have reached a point of political despair.
The Republican blockade policy cannot explain why the eavesdropping of foreign heads of state is allowed or the killing of innocent children by drones overseas.
It can't explain why the National Security Agency is collecting data on the private lives of Americans and why whistleblowers are being punished who disclose government misconduct.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, was murdered without trial, and why public funding and spending limits are being circumvented during the presidential election.
It does not justify the findings of a report that says the White House's efforts to keep the media quieting are the "most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration."
And recently, it cannot excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the adoption of the Affordable Care Act.
I don't know if that's what I should have expected.
Whether I should have understood at 18 that government work could contradict the political campaigns preceding it.
Clearly, the MPs office is not a predictable course, as an opposition party and random events such as the Newtown massacre shape the public discussion.
But when I look at the above examples, they seem to be largely elected by the government itself.
And that bothers me the most.
I re-elected Obama in 2012, not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney represented a confusing and unfermented alternative, he did not seem to be able to set his direction and positions.
I had the impression that a second term for Obama, free from the pressure of future elections, would fulfill the hope we had heard of for so long.
Yet by sinking approval ratings for Obama to below 45% this week, the return to 2008 through this book has become all the harder.
It awakens in me the longing for the many promises that have dissolved into thin air.
This week I read a section in the book that describes how Obama had to pocket a heavy loss to Clinton in the Pennsylvania primaries.
In a meeting with the election workers after the decision, he told his staff they needed to get back on track and follow the purpose of their cause.
"I want us to find our magic again," he said.
We need to remember who we are.
It's five years later, Mr. President, and I couldn't agree with you any more.
The views expressed in this commentary are exclusively those of Nathaniel Morris.
